<h2 class="section-head">SL-28 and SL-34: <em>The Varieties That Define the Cup</em></h2>

<p class="body">SL-28 and SL-34 are the most important factor in Kenyan cup quality. Both were developed by Scott Laboratories (hence "SL") in the 1930s during a colonial-era program to identify drought-resistant and high-yielding coffee varieties for Kenyan production. Neither was selected for flavor, but both happened to produce flavor profiles that specialty buyers now prize highly.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>SL-28</strong> is the flagship. Drought-resistant, suited to lower-rainfall areas within Kenya's highlands, and the producer of the blackcurrant and phosphoric acidity that defines the best Kenyan cups. The phosphoric acidity in SL-28 coffee is a specific chemical compound that registers on the palate as bright, juicy, almost effervescent, and tied to flavors of blackcurrant, cassis, and dark berry. It is not the same as the citric acidity in Ethiopian washed or the malic acidity in some Colombian coffees: it is distinctively Kenyan, and distinctively SL-28.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>SL-34</strong> complements SL-28 in the cup by adding body and complexity. Where SL-28 delivers brightness and specific berry character, SL-34 adds weight, depth, and a wine-like finish that makes the best Kenyan coffees feel complete rather than one-dimensional. Washing stations that process SL-28 and SL-34 cherry together produce the full Kenyan profile: brightness and specificity from SL-28, body and length from SL-34.</p>

<p class="body">Together, the two varieties create the Kenyan cup identity more than any other single factor. High altitude and skilled processing allow the genetics to express fully, but the genetics are the foundation. This is why Kenyan coffee planted at similar altitudes in other African countries with different varietals does not taste Kenyan: the flavor is in the genes, not just the place.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Kenyan Growing Regions: <em>Where the Best Lots Come From</em></h2>

<p class="body"><strong>Nyeri.</strong> The benchmark region for Kenyan specialty. Located in the central highlands at 1,700 to 2,000 MASL on the slopes of Mount Kenya, Nyeri produces the most complex and structured cups in Kenyan coffee. Red volcanic soil, consistent rainfall, and the highest concentration of specialty-focused cooperatives combine to make Nyeri the region most consistently represented at the top of Kenyan auction results. Tasting notes: blackcurrant, grapefruit, tomato, wine-like finish, full body, long aftertaste. If you have never had Kenyan coffee, a well-sourced Nyeri washing station lot is where to start.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Kirinyaga.</strong> Adjacent to Nyeri on different slopes of Mount Kenya, Kirinyaga produces cups that tasters often describe as more delicate and fruit-forward than the structured intensity of Nyeri. The blackcurrant character is present but less assertive; the red fruit notes (cranberry, red currant) are more prominent. Some buyers prefer Kirinyaga for its approachability; Nyeri devotees find it less complex. Both represent the best of Kenyan specialty and the comparison between them is worth making if you are serious about the origin.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Murang'a.</strong> On the southern slopes of Mount Kenya, Murang'a produces consistent and balanced Kenyan specialty without the intense structure of Nyeri or the delicate fruit of Kirinyaga. Good Murang'a lots offer the core Kenyan character (blackcurrant, bright acidity, full body) in a more accessible form. For buyers who find Nyeri too intense or acidic, Murang'a is a useful middle ground.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Embu.</strong> On the eastern slopes of Mount Kenya, Embu produces coffees with more citrus-forward character: lemon, orange zest, and citric acidity rather than the phosphoric blackcurrant of SL-28-dominant lots. Embu coffees tend toward lighter body and brighter fruit. Interesting for buyers who want to explore how the same varieties express differently across slopes of the same mountain.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Machakos.</strong> Lower altitude than the Mount Kenya regions, Machakos produces more approachable Kenyan coffees with less intense acidity and more chocolate-adjacent notes. Less celebrated in specialty circles than Nyeri or Kirinyaga, but useful for buyers who want Kenyan character without the full intensity of the central highlands.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Kenya AA and AB Grading: <em>What It Actually Tells You</em></h2>

<p class="body">The Kenya AA grading designation is not a quality indicator. It is a bean size grade. AA designates beans that pass through screen size 18 (approximately 7.2mm in diameter). AB is a combined grade for beans at screen sizes 15 and 16. The grading system was designed for export standardization, not cup quality evaluation.</p>

<p class="body">The practical implication: larger beans (AA) do not inherently produce better coffee. Bean size correlates weakly with altitude (higher-altitude cherries develop more slowly and may produce larger seeds) but does not determine cup quality. A Nyeri AB from a top cooperative processed with care and skill can produce a cup that is more complex, sweeter, and more interesting than a Kenya AA from a lower-altitude region with average processing.</p>

<p class="body">This matters when buying. A bag labeled "Kenya AA" from a generic roaster tells you the bean size grade and nothing else. A bag labeled "Kenya AA - Nyeri County - Gakuyuini Cooperative - Washed - SL-28/SL-34 - Roasted 2026-06-15" tells you something worth knowing. The additional information is what distinguishes specialty sourcing from commodity sourcing using the same "AA" label.</p>

<p class="body">At the retail level, "Kenya AA" functions as a marketing premium more than a quality signal. Do not buy based on the AA designation alone. Buy based on region, washing station or cooperative name, variety, processing method, and roast date.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Cooperative Structure: <em>How Kenyan Specialty Reaches You</em></h2>

<p class="body">Most Kenyan specialty coffee is not grown on large estates. It is produced by thousands of smallholder farmers, many with less than half a hectare, who bring their harvested cherry to a cooperative washing station for processing. The washing station (called a "factory" in Kenyan coffee terminology, a colonial-era holdover) receives cherry from dozens or hundreds of smallholders, sorts it, processes it through washed fermentation tanks, and dries it on raised beds.</p>

<p class="body">This cooperative structure has significant quality implications. A washing station that sorts carefully, manages fermentation times, and dries on raised beds in clean conditions can elevate the quality of smallholder lots beyond what individual small-farm processing could achieve. The washing station becomes the unit of traceability and quality control. Specialty roasters who travel to source in Kenya build relationships with specific washing stations and cooperatives, and the provenance information on the bag ("Gakuyuini Washing Station, Nyeri County") refers to the cooperative processing unit, not an individual farm.</p>

<p class="body">This is why the washing station name matters on a Kenyan coffee bag. It is the point at which quality was either controlled or not, and the most reliable indicator of what is in the cup beyond the regional designation.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Processing: <em>Washed, and Why It Matters</em></h2>

<p class="body">Kenyan coffee is processed almost exclusively by the washed method, and this is central to the cup profile. Washed processing removes the fruit material from the coffee seed before drying, which means the flavor in the cup comes entirely from the bean's intrinsic character: the genetics of SL-28 and SL-34, the altitude, the soil. There is no natural-process fruit sweetness buffering or modifying the acidity.</p>

<p class="body">The double-fermented washed process common at top Kenyan cooperatives extends fermentation beyond the standard single-pass: cherry is fermented, the mucilage layer is removed, and the beans ferment again in water before washing and drying. This extended fermentation produces the particularly clean, bright, and complex cups that make high-end Kenyan specialty distinctive from standard washed African coffees.</p>

<p class="body">Natural and honey-processed Kenyan coffees exist in small quantities at experimental farms, but they represent a tiny fraction of Kenyan production and are unusual enough that you should treat them as specialty curiosities rather than typical examples of the origin. For a full breakdown of processing methods, see the <a href="/learn/coffee-processing-methods" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">coffee processing methods guide</a>.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Flavor Expectations: <em>What to Taste</em></h2>

<p class="body">A well-sourced and well-roasted Kenyan coffee from Nyeri or Kirinyaga should deliver: blackcurrant (cassis), grapefruit or pomelo, often a savory tomato note that registers as umami, wine-like acidity in the finish, full body relative to other African origins, and a long, dry, tannin-adjacent aftertaste that lingers. These are not metaphors constructed to make the coffee sound interesting. They are specific flavor compounds in the cup.</p>

<p class="body">Light to medium roast is mandatory to taste this. Darker roasting flattens the phosphoric acidity that produces the blackcurrant and grapefruit notes into generic bitterness. A medium-dark roasted Kenyan tastes like a generic dark coffee with some fruit in the background. A light-roasted Kenyan from a top Nyeri washing station, brewed properly, tastes like nothing else in the world of coffee.</p>

<p class="body">Brew parameters: Kenyan washed coffee rewards slightly higher water temperature (93-95°C) in pour-over to ensure full extraction of the complex flavor compounds. A medium-coarse grind on a pour-over like a Hario V60 or Kalita Wave gives the clearest expression of the origin character. French press works but softens the acidity and adds body that can mute the specific fruit notes.</p>

